<p class="ltx_p" id="S2.p5.4">where <math alttext="\mathcal{T}" class="ltx_Math" display="inline" id="S2.p5.4.m1.1"><semantics id="S2.p5.4.m1.1a"><mi class="ltx_font_mathcaligraphic" id="S2.p5.4.m1.1.1" xref="S2.p5.4.m1.1.1.cmml">𝒯</mi><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content" id="S2.p5.4.m1.1b"><ci id="S2.p5.4.m1.1.1.cmml" xref="S2.p5.4.m1.1.1">𝒯</ci></annotation-xml><annotation encoding="application/x-tex" id="S2.p5.4.m1.1c">\mathcal{T}</annotation><annotation encoding="application/x-llamapun" id="S2.p5.4.m1.1d">caligraphic_T</annotation></semantics></math> is the trace of the stress-energy tensor.</p>
</div>
<div class="ltx_para" id="S2.p6">
<p class="ltx_p" id="S2.p6.2">By equating the two equations (<a class="ltx_ref" href="https://arxiv.org/html/2503.08236v1#S2.E10" title="In II Modified Entropy Gravity ‣ Cosmological Implications of Modified Entropic Gravity"><span class="ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">10</span></a>) and (<a class="ltx_ref" href="https://arxiv.org/html/2503.08236v1#S2.E11" title="In II Modified Entropy Gravity ‣ Cosmological Implications of Modified Entropic Gravity"><span class="ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">11</span></a>), the modified Einstein equations in our entropic gravity scenario are obtained as follows <cite class="ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite"><a class="ltx_ref" href="https://arxiv.org/html/2503.08236v1#bib.bib78" title="">Sheykhi:2012vf </a></cite></p>
<table class="ltx_equation ltx_eqn_table" id="S2.E12">
<tbody><tr class="ltx_equation ltx_eqn_row ltx_align_baseline">
<td class="ltx_eqn_cell ltx_eqn_center_padleft"></td>
