<p class="ltx_p" id="S2.p16.1">where <math alttext="f_{0}" class="ltx_Math" display="inline" id="S2.p16.1.m1.1"><semantics id="S2.p16.1.m1.1a"><msub id="S2.p16.1.m1.1.1" xref="S2.p16.1.m1.1.1.cmml"><mi id="S2.p16.1.m1.1.1.2" xref="S2.p16.1.m1.1.1.2.cmml">f</mi><mn id="S2.p16.1.m1.1.1.3" xref="S2.p16.1.m1.1.1.3.cmml">0</mn></msub><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content" id="S2.p16.1.m1.1b"><apply id="S2.p16.1.m1.1.1.cmml" xref="S2.p16.1.m1.1.1"><csymbol cd="ambiguous" id="S2.p16.1.m1.1.1.1.cmml" xref="S2.p16.1.m1.1.1">subscript</csymbol><ci id="S2.p16.1.m1.1.1.2.cmml" xref="S2.p16.1.m1.1.1.2">𝑓</ci><cn id="S2.p16.1.m1.1.1.3.cmml" type="integer" xref="S2.p16.1.m1.1.1.3">0</cn></apply></annotation-xml><annotation encoding="application/x-tex" id="S2.p16.1.m1.1c">f_{0}</annotation><annotation encoding="application/x-llamapun" id="S2.p16.1.m1.1d">italic_f start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 0 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT</annotation></semantics></math> is the value of the function of temperature correction at the present time.</p>
</div>
<div class="ltx_para" id="S2.p17">
<p class="ltx_p" id="S2.p17.3">In our study, we consider neutrinos to be massless. Therefore, the radiation component here consists of two components: photons and massless neutrinos. For the energy density of photons, we have <cite class="ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite"><a class="ltx_ref" href="https://arxiv.org/html/2503.08236v1#bib.bib94" title="">WMAP:2012nax </a></cite></p>
<table class="ltx_equation ltx_eqn_table" id="S2.E46">
