<p class="ltx_p" id="S3.SS2.p2.1">where <math alttext="\tilde{H}" class="ltx_Math" display="inline" id="S3.SS2.p2.1.m1.1"><semantics id="S3.SS2.p2.1.m1.1a"><mover accent="true" id="S3.SS2.p2.1.m1.1.1" xref="S3.SS2.p2.1.m1.1.1.cmml"><mi id="S3.SS2.p2.1.m1.1.1.2" xref="S3.SS2.p2.1.m1.1.1.2.cmml">H</mi><mo id="S3.SS2.p2.1.m1.1.1.1" xref="S3.SS2.p2.1.m1.1.1.1.cmml">~</mo></mover><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content" id="S3.SS2.p2.1.m1.1b"><apply id="S3.SS2.p2.1.m1.1.1.cmml" xref="S3.SS2.p2.1.m1.1.1"><ci id="S3.SS2.p2.1.m1.1.1.1.cmml" xref="S3.SS2.p2.1.m1.1.1.1">~</ci><ci id="S3.SS2.p2.1.m1.1.1.2.cmml" xref="S3.SS2.p2.1.m1.1.1.2">𝐻</ci></apply></annotation-xml><annotation encoding="application/x-tex" id="S3.SS2.p2.1.m1.1c">\tilde{H}</annotation><annotation encoding="application/x-llamapun" id="S3.SS2.p2.1.m1.1d">over~ start_ARG italic_H end_ARG</annotation></semantics></math> is the Hubble parameter of the model and its relation for the modified entropic cosmology (MEC) is given in Eq. (<a class="ltx_ref" href="https://arxiv.org/html/2503.08236v1#S2.E51" title="In II Modified Entropy Gravity ‣ Cosmological Implications of Modified Entropic Gravity"><span class="ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">51</span></a>). For the angular diameter distance, we use the following equation <cite class="ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite"><a class="ltx_ref" href="https://arxiv.org/html/2503.08236v1#bib.bib90" title="">SDSS:2009ocz </a>; <a class="ltx_ref" href="https://arxiv.org/html/2503.08236v1#bib.bib96" title="">Nesseris:2012tt </a></cite></p>
