/semantics></math> is the physical angular diameter distance in Eq. (<a class="ltx_ref" href="https://arxiv.org/html/2503.08236v1#S3.E61" title="In III.3 CMB Data ‣ III Observational Data ‣ Cosmological Implications of Modified Entropic Gravity"><span class="ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">61</span></a>), while <math alttext="r_{s}(z_{*})" class="ltx_Math" display="inline" id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1"><semantics id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1a"><mrow id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.cmml"><msub id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.3" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.3.cmml"><mi id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.3.2" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.3.2.cmml">r</mi><mi id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.3.3" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.3.3.cmml">s</mi></msub><mo id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.2" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.2.cmml">⁢</mo><mrow id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.1.1" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.1.1.1.cmml"><mo id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.1.1.2" stretchy="false" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.1.1.1.cmml">(</mo><msub id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.1.1.1" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.1.1.1.cmml"><mi id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.1.1.1.2" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.1.1.1.2.cmml">z</mi><mo id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.1.1.1.3" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.1.1.1.3.cmml">∗</mo></msub><mo id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.1.1.3" stretchy="false" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.1.1.1.cmml">)</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content" id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1b"><apply id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.cmml" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1"><times id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.2.cmml" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.2"></times><apply id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.3.cmml" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.3"><csymbol cd="ambiguous" id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.3.1.cmml" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.3">subscript</csymbol><ci id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.3.2.cmml" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.3.2">𝑟</ci><ci id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.3.3.cmml" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.3.3">𝑠</ci></apply><apply id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.1.1.1.cmml" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.1.1"><csymbol cd="ambiguous" id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.1.1.1.1.cmml" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.1.1">subscript</csymbol><ci id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.1.1.1.2.cmml" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.1.1.1.2">𝑧</ci><times id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.1.1.1.3.cmml" xref="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1.1.1.1.1.3"></times></apply></apply></annotation-xml><annotation encoding="application/x-tex" id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1c">r_{s}(z_{*})</annotation><annotation encoding="application/x-llamapun" id="S3.SS3.p3.4.m3.1d">italic_r start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_s end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_z start_POSTSUBSCRIPT ∗ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT )</annotation></semantics></math> is the associated comoving sound horizon at <math alttext="z_{*}" class="ltx_Math" display="inline" id="S3.SS3.p3.5.m4.1"><semantics id="S3.SS3.p3.5.m4.1a"><msub id="S3.SS3.p3.5.m4.1.1" xref="S3.SS3.p3.5.m4.1.1.cmml"><mi id="S3.SS3.p3.5.m4.1.1.2" xref="S3.SS3.p3.5.m4.1.1.2.cmml">z</mi><mo id="S3.SS3.p3.5.m4.1.1.3" xref="S3.SS3.p3.5.m4.1.1.3.cmml">∗</mo></msub><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content" id="S3.SS3.p3.5.m4.1b"><apply id="S3.SS3.p3.5.m4.1.1.cmml" xref="S3.SS3.p3.5.m4.1.1"><csymbol cd="ambiguous" id="S3.SS3.p3.5.m4.1.1.1.cmml" xref="S3.SS3.p3.5.m4.1.1">subscript</csymbol><ci id="S3.SS3.p3.5.m4.1.1.2.cmml" xref="S3.SS3.p3.5.m4.1.1.2">𝑧</ci><times id="S3.SS3.p3.5.m4.1.1.3.cmml" xref="S3.SS3.p3.5.m4.1.1.3"></times></apply></annotation-xml><annotation encoding="application/x-tex" id="S3.SS3.p3.5.m4.1c">z_{*}</annotation><annotation encoding="application/x-llamapun" id="S3.SS3.p3.5.m4.1d">italic_z start_POSTSUBSCRIPT ∗ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT</annotation></semantics></math> and is determined by Eq. (<a class="ltx_ref" href="https://arxiv.org/html/2503.08236v1#S3.E55" title="In III.2 BAO Data ‣ III Observational Data ‣ Cosmological Implications of Modified Entropic Gravity"><span class="ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">55</span></a>).</p>
</div>
<div class="ltx_para" id="S3.SS3.p4">
<p class="ltx_p" id="S3.SS3.p4.2">Chen et al. <cite class="ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite"><a class="ltx_ref" href="https://arxiv.org/html/2503.08236v1#bib.bib106" title="">Chen:2018dbv </a></cite> have compared the analysis of the full CMB spectrum with the distance history method by constraining several dark energy models and have shown that the results of both methods are in perfect agreement. Therefore, in the present analysis, we consider the combined CMB likelihood (Planck 2018 TT, TE, EE + lowE) by considering <math alttext="X_{i}^{\mathrm{obs}}=\{R,\,l_{a},\,\Omega_{b0}h^{2}\}=\{1.7502,\,301.4707,\,0.%
